<body>
    <div class="header-info">
        <p><strong>Subject:</strong> Promoting Global Peace Education</p>
        <p><strong>Topic:</strong> Upholding Human Dignity</p>
    </div>

    <h1>Upholding Human Dignity and Human Rights</h1>

    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>Upholding Human Dignity and Human Rights as an important part of Peace Education. Human dignity means that every person has value and deserves respect simply because they are human. Because of this dignity, everyone is entitled to basic rights that protect their freedom, safety, and well-being. After the tragedies of World War II, the United Nations created the Universal Declaration of Human Rights in 1948 to protect the rights and dignity of all people. Understanding these rights helps us build a more peaceful, fair, and respectful society.</p>

    <h2>1. Historical Context of Human Dignity as a Component of Peace Education</h2>
    <p>Human dignity is the fundamental innate worth of a human being. It is the belief that all people hold a special value that is tied solely to their humanity.</p>
    <h6>
        <li><strong>Inherent Worth:</strong> It has nothing to do with class, race, gender, religion, abilities, or any other factor other than being human.</li>
        <li><strong>Universal Right:</strong> Everyone young, old, rich, or poor—shares the right to be treated with dignity.</li>
        <li><strong>Life Potential:</strong> Every human has the right to lead a dignified life and fulfill his or her potential.</li>
        <li><strong>Justification for Rights:</strong> Human dignity justifies human rights; recognizing it prevents cycles of destruction and violence in society.</li>
    </h6>

    <h2>2. What are Human Rights?</h2>
    <p>Human rights refers to norms that aim to protect people from political, legal, and social abuses.</p>
    <h6>
        <li><strong>Universal and Inalienable:</strong> These rights are inherent to everyone regardless of nationality, sex, religion, or status, and are not granted by any state.</li>
        <li><strong>Interdependent and Indivisible:</strong> The United Nations defines human rights as being interconnected and incapable of being separated.</li>
    </h6>

    <h2>3. Classification of Human Rights</h2>
    <p>Rights are divided into various categories based on their nature and origin:</p>
    <table>
        <thead>
            <h5>
                <h3>Type of Right</h3>
                <h3>Description</h3>
                <h3>Examples</h3>
            </h5>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <h5>
                <h4>1. Natural Rights</h4>
                <h4>Rights considered inherent and integral to human nature.</h4>
                <h4>Rights of the mind and acting for one's own comfort/happiness.</h4>
            </h5>
            <h5>
                <h4>2. Moral Rights</h4>
                <h4>Based on general principles of fairness and justice; often aspirations or ideals.</h4>
                <h4>No one can change your work without your permission.</h4>
            </h5>
            <h5>
                <h4>3. Fundamental Rights</h4>
                <h4>Basic rights upon which the enjoyment of other rights depends; cannot be taken away.</td>
                <h4>The right to life.</h4>
            </h5>
            <h5>
                <h4>4. Legal Rights</h4>
                <h4>Also known as positive rights; these are laid down and protected by the law of the state.</h4>
                <h4>Uniform rights open to all regardless of race or culture.</h4>
            </h5>
            <h5>
                <h4>5. Civil & Political Rights</h4>
                <h4>Granted by the government to provide the basis for social and civilized life.</h4>
                <h4>Freedom of speech, assembly, and the right to vote.</h4>
            </h5>
            <h5>
                <h4>6. Economic, Social, & Cultural Rights</h4>
                <h4>Entitlements to eradicate social inequality and economic imbalances.</h4>
                <h4>Rights to work, education, healthcare, and social security.</h4>
            </h5>
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>4. Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR)</h2>
    <p>The UDHR was announced by the United Nations on December 10, 1948, to foster international peace and prevent a repeat of the horrors of World War II. It consists of 30 articles outlining the freedoms that belong to everyone.</p>
    <p><strong>Key articles include:</strong></p>
    <h6>
        <li><strong>Article 1:</strong> All human beings are born free and equal in dignity and rights.</li>
        <li><strong>Article 3:</strong> Everyone has the right to life, liberty, and security of person.</li>
        <li><strong>Article 5:</strong> Freedom from torture or cruel, inhuman, or degrading treatment.</li>
        <li><strong>Article 26:</strong> The right to education, which shall be free and compulsory at the elementary stages.</li>
    </h6>

    <h2>5. Rights and Responsibilities</h2>
    <p>While we expect our rights to be respected, we must also undertake corresponding responsibilities.</p>
    <h6>
        <li><strong>Respect for Others:</strong> We cannot think only of our own rights without considering the rights of others.</li>
        <li><strong>Non-Violation:</strong> When exercising our rights, we must take care not to violate or deny the rights of others.</li>
        <li><strong>The Golden Rule:</strong> Treat others as you would want to be treated.</li>
    </h6>
    <p><em>Example: A teacher has the right to a fair wage and freedom of expression, but also the responsibility to give their best effort and treat students with respect.</em></p>

    <h2>6. Historical Context of the UDHR</h2>
    <p>The Universal Declaration of Human Rights (UDHR) was a direct response to the "traumatic events of the Second World War".</p>
    <h6>
        <li>The extermination of nearly 17 million people during the Holocaust, including 6 million Jews, horrified the world and led to the establishment of the United Nations in June 1945.</li>
        <li>Eleanor Roosevelt, the former First Lady of the United States, led the representatives from 50 member states to devise the list of rights in 1948.</li>
    </h6>

    <h2>7. Legal Protections in the Philippines</h2>
    <p>The module connects international standards to the 1987 Philippine Constitution:</p>
    <h6>
        <li><strong>Right to Life:</strong> Under Article 3, Section 1, "life" is protected by due process and extends to all "limbs and faculties" by which life is enjoyed.</li>
        <li><strong>Freedom from Torture:</strong> Section 12 (2) prohibits the use of torture, force, violence, threat, or secret detention places.</li>
        <li><strong>Prisoner Rights:</strong> Section 19 (2) prohibits the use of "substandard or inadequate penal facilities under subhuman conditions".</li>
    </h6>

    <h2>8. Specific Nuances of Freedom from Slavery (Article 4)</h2>
    <p>The document distinguishes between three types of labor exploitation:</p>
    <h6>
        <li><strong>Slavery:</strong> When one person actually "owns you like a piece of property".</li>
        <li><strong>Servitude:</strong> Living on a person's premises and working for them without the ability to leave, though they do not "own" you.</li>
        <li><strong>Forced Labour:</strong> Work performed under the threat of punishment that you did not agree to.</li>
    </h6>
    <p><strong>Exceptions:</strong> Work done as part of a prison sentence, during a state of emergency, or as part of normal civic obligations (like jury service) is not considered prohibited forced labor.</p>

    <h2>9. Categorization of Rights</h2>
    <p>The UDHR articles are grouped into five major types of rights:</p>
    <h6>
        <li><strong>Civil Rights:</strong> Include Articles 3, 4, 5, 9, 10, 11, 12, 13, 16, and 19.</li>
        <li><strong>Political Rights:</strong> Include Articles 14, 20, and 21.</li>
        <li><strong>Economic Rights:</strong> Include Articles 17 and 23.</li>
        <li><strong>Social Rights:</strong> Include Articles 22 and 24.</li>
        <li><strong>Standard of Living:</strong> Includes the right to food, nutrition, clothing, and housing so that people can be "full participants in ordinary, everyday interaction" without shame.</li>
    </h6>

    <h2>10. Educational Philosophy</h2>
    <p>The module also briefly mentions Maria Montessori's Principles as a component of Peace Education, emphasizing that individuals should be "free to move, free to choose their own work, and follow their interests".</p>

